&lt;/ul&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Solution] C++ std::underflow_error — Arithmetic Underflow Fix</title><link>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/cpp/underflowerror/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/cpp/underflowerror/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="solution-c-stdunderflow_error--arithmetic-underflow-fix"&gt;[Solution] C++ std::underflow_error — Arithmetic Underflow Fix&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;code&gt;std::underflow_error&lt;/code&gt; is thrown when an arithmetic operation produces a result that is too small in magnitude to be represented as a finite floating-point number (denormalized or zero). This typically happens with extremely small floating-point calculations where the result underflows the minimum representable positive value.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="why-stdunderflow_error-occurs"&gt;Why std::underflow_error Occurs&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Common causes include multiplying very small floating-point numbers together, computing extremely small exponential values, dividing by very large numbers repeatedly, and accumulating rounding errors in floating-point arithmetic.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>